7 .
a group of tasks that can be executed in parallel without requiring data shuffle
A stage in Spark is a set of parallel tasks that can be executed without shuffle. Stages are created based on shuffle boundaries,
where wide transformations like joins or groupBy trigger a new stage.

8.
a unit of execution triggered when an action is called on a DataFrame or RDD
A job in Spark is triggered by an action and represents the execution of a DAG. It is divided into stages based on shuffle boundaries,
and each stage is further divided into tasks executed in parallel.


9. A task is the smallest unit of execution in Spark, where each task processes one partition of data and runs on an executor core in parallel.”

10.
Narrow dependency occurs when each output partition depends on a single input partition, so no shuffle is required. filter , select,map
Wide dependency occurs when output partitions depend on multiple input partitions, requiring shuffle and creating a new stage.” groupby,join,reduceByKey

11 
Spark does not store every intermediate result on disk
👉 Instead, it keeps track of how data was derived (lineage graph)
So if something fails:
👉 It recomputes lost data using transformations
Spark handles failures using lineage-based recomputation. If a task fails, it is retried. If an executor fails, lost partitions are recomputed using lineage. 
In case of stage failure, the entire stage is re-executed, while driver failure causes the whole job to restart

13
Checkpointing in Spark is the process of saving data to reliable storage and truncating lineage to avoid expensive recomputation.
It is mainly used when lineage becomes long or for iterative and streaming workloads

14 
Shuffle in Spark is the process of redistributing data across partitions during wide transformations like joins and aggregations,
ensuring that related data is grouped together for processing

15 
Shuffle is expensive because it involves network transfer, disk I/O, and serialization, which are significantly slower than in-memory computation.

